Xuanzang did not study mountains and forests, but he revered the Way of the world. He was a wise man of the wilds, a scholar who did not waste his days by the rivers and seas. If he entered the countryside, he would be upright; if his country advanced into the mountains and forests, scholars would flourish in the passes. Even if he wandered as a hermit, he would not be as wise as the gatekeeper. He held wisdom and power, observed the sun and learned deeply. Even if he thought of the Way, he would not be careless in his hometown. Grass sprouts from the marketplace. Even if the Yangtze River is grand, there is a spring by the mountains and forests. After he established the principles of the city, he commanded the Yangtze River. The great rites and strict laws observe the Way and improve the country.

